  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations to Vermont in FY2026 to date total $321M. Award activity consists of 3,516 awards, with an average award size of $91.3K. Obligations fell 63.4% year over year. Obligations by fiscal year show prior peaks and troughs: FY21 $394M, FY22 $506M, FY23 $424M, FY24 $920M, FY25 $877M, and FY26 $321M. The Department of Defense provides the largest share of obligations with $202M, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs with $51.2M and the Department of Homeland Security with $33.7M. Top vendors include GLOBALFOUNDRIES U.S. 2 LLC ($82.5M) and SCIENCE APPLICATIONS INTERNATIONAL CORPORATION ($45M). Leading industries by obligation include Semiconductor and Related Device Manufacturing ($82.5M) and Engineering Services ($54.3M). All figures are contract obligations; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has federal contracting in Vermont changed year over year?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 63.4% year over year. Total obligations in FY2026 to date are $321M, compared with FY25 $877M and FY24 $920M. Annual obligations prior to FY24 were FY23 $424M, FY22 $506M, and FY21 $394M."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and vendors dominate federal contracting in Vermont?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense leads with $202M in obligations, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs at $51.2M and the Department of Homeland Security at $33.7M. Top vendors include GLOBALFOUNDRIES U.S. 2 LLC ($82.5M), SCIENCE APPLICATIONS INTERNATIONAL CORPORATION ($45M), and MIND COMPUTING, INC. ($28.1M). Leading industry categories include Semiconductor and Related Device Manufacturing ($82.5M) and Engineering Services ($54.3M)."
      }
    ]
  },
